Q11: The ideal climate treaty would be one that is comprehensive, binding, and equitable. It would set ambitious yet achievable targets for reducing greenhouse gas emissions, with mechanisms for enforcement and penalties for non-compliance. It would also provide support for developing nations in the form of technology transfer and climate finance, ensuring that they can grow sustainably without repeating the high-emission industrialization patterns of the past. Furthermore, it would prioritize adaptation measures for communities already affected by climate change and include strategies to preserve biodiversity and promote sustainable land use. Finally, it would have a dynamic structure to be updated regularly based on the latest scientific findings and technological advancements.
